Yeonjun I think I'm in love with you and I want you to know about it. Miracle group no.1
NAVER: #YEONJUNâ€™s GGUM tops Korean and Japanese charts... first mixtape, music power  Yeonjun topped album charts with his first solo activity. According to album sales statistics site Hanteo, GGUM ranked #1 on the Daily Album Chart (October 29).  It did well on the Korean and Japanese charts. It also reached #1 on Japanese Oricon Daily Single Ranking (October 28) and Circle Chart Daily Retail Album Chart (October 29).  GGUM is a hip-hop genre song. It compares confidence and ambition on stage to gum. The simple and unique chorus lyrics, "GGUM jilgeong" are impressive.  The performance is also attractive. The choreography utilizes his long limbs. An official said, "He has the stage presence and dance lines that are worthy of a representative K-pop dancer."  GGUM also showed off its music power. First, it achieved 1st place on Worldwide iTunes Song Chart. It also reached the top of iTunes 'Top Song' in a total of 33 countries/regions.  On the US Billboard chart, it ranked 4th on the 'World Digital Song Sales' for 2 consecutive weeks. It received much love, such as winning a trophy on Mnet's 'M Countdown'. (@913records on twt)

I am deeply disappointed by the production quality of this song. It seems as though Hybe has made minimal effort in terms of music composition or catering to Yeonjunâ€™s immense talent. The track feels as if it was pulled from a "rejection list," rather than something thoughtfully crafted for him. This wasted potential is frustrating, especially given the caliber of an artist like Yeonjun.  Moreover, I fail to understand why many K-pop idols today seem obsessed with incorporating profanity or explicit content into their work. Was the use of the F-word or any form of 18+ material really necessary in this context? K-pop once stood out for its unique and culturally infused sound, but sadly, that seems to be fading away. The genre now feels more like an attempt to mimic Western trends, rather than preserving the distinctiveness that once made it so special.  As a long-time K-pop fan, having followed the genre since the second generation, I am disheartened by the current direction. The music no longer carries the same charm, and the once-intricate melodies and fun elements have been replaced with a generic approach aimed at pleasing the Western market. What once made K-pop exciting and different now feels watered down and unoriginal. The current generation of songs lacks the staying power that made previous eras so iconic.  It seems more and more that companies are exploiting the fanbase for profit, rather than focusing on delivering the innovative and catchy music they promised. This shift is disappointing, and I find myself longing for the golden era of K-pop, when the music was not only memorable but also uniquely Korean, and YES, Every songs are sounding same!!!!!!
